{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Renamed files appear in their own category and are not also counted as a deletion plus an addition.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Real failure boundary is the CLI↔git subprocess interaction: rename detection depends on actual git status/diff semantics and flags. A mocked git response can miss failures where git emits add+delete instead of rename, or where subprocess output parsing differs from fixtures. Higher levels are disqualified because behavior text is only about git/CLI categorization (no AI/ML decisions, no multi-agent pipeline).","test_description":"Create a real temp git repo, commit a file, rename it (`git mv`), run the CLI as a subprocess, and assert report shows 1 rename and 0 add/0 delete for that change.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.65,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Diffs that include binary files do not cause the tool to crash; binary files are counted in the output.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Crash risk often appears at real subprocess/encoding boundaries (git output, bytes handling, exit behavior), which mocks can hide. The behavior explicitly involves binary diffs from a real repo state, so real git + filesystem are the minimum reliable boundary. No LLM/model dependency or agent chain is present.","test_description":"Create a real repo, add and modify a binary file (for example random bytes), run the CLI subprocess, assert non-zero crash does not occur and binary change is included in counts.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.75,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Running the tool on a repository that has no commits yet produces an empty report rather than an error.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This failure is typically driven by real git behavior on an unborn branch (fatal/no-HEAD cases), which is subprocess-specific and easy to mask with stubs. Integration fakes can simulate this, but the minimum to catch real CLI/git failure modes is System. Behavior text contains no AI/ML or multi-step agentic content.","test_description":"Initialize a fresh repo with no commits, run CLI subprocess from repo root, assert exit is successful and stdout is a valid empty structured report.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The counts in the report match the actual change history of the repository being analyzed.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is an end-to-end correctness claim against real repository history; failures can arise from git command selection, revision ranges, and subprocess output interpretation. Mocked history risks asserting the same mistaken assumptions as implementation. No behavior text indicates model-output quality or agent pipelines, so Agentic/Workflow are disqualified.","test_description":"Build a real repo history with known adds/deletes/renames/modifies across commits, run CLI subprocess for the target range, and assert category counts exactly match the known ground truth.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.75,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The output is identical whether the changes being analyzed are staged or unstaged.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Staged vs unstaged semantics come from real git index and working-tree behavior; module-level mocks can hide mismatches in how the CLI invokes git for each state. Because correctness depends on actual repository/index state transitions, System is the minimum reliable level. No AI/ML decision quality or multi-agent sequencing appears in the behavior text.","test_description